	abstract = {Carboniferous glacial deposits belonging to the Dwyka Formation of the Karoo Sequence fill a glaciated basin along the northwestern margin of the large Karoo Basin. Six lithofacies were recognised in the glacials which have a maximum thickness in excess of 100 m. The diamictite facies is subdivided in a massive homogeneous, a faintly bedded homogeneous, a laminated and a bedded heterogeneous subfacies, which respectively represent basal till, proximal and distal waterlain tills and reworked till. The conglomerate, sandstone, sandstone—siltstone—shale and sandstone—carbonate facies were formed by glacial outwash and minor deltaic and beach sedimentation. Mud with ice-rafted debris constitutes the varved mudstone facies, while the dark shale facies consists of post-glacial shallow-water beds. The palaeotopography, clast characteristics, sedimentary facies and small-scale erosional features were applied to determined the direction of ice flow and to establish a four-stage model for the glaciation. During the valley glaciation stage ice flowed southwards down the Ghaap escarpment, largely modifying the pre-glacial erosional features. This was followed by an ice-sheet stage with the spreading centre of the ice over the Transvaal Highlands. During its main phase the ice selectively eroded the area depending on the basal thermal regime. With deglaciation, basal till was deposited by grounded ice, but as the ice became buoyant, initially proximal and later distal waterlain tills were deposited. These two stages represent the Older glaciation terminated by the retreat of the ice and a subsequent uplift of the area. The Younger glaciation started also in the north with a minor valley glaciation stage during which lodgement tills, glacial outwash, deltaic beds and beach sediments were deposited. This was followed by a marine transgression and finally an ice-shelf stage when ice flowed down the Ghaap escarpment into the embayment formed by the Prieska Basin. Deposition of proximal and distal waterlain tills by basal melt-out took place. Varved sediments with minor ice-rafted debris locally overlying the tills represent the final retreat of the ice.},
