	shorttitle = {Biomarker maturity parameters for high maturities},
	url = {http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/014663809090139Q},
	doi = {10.1016/0146-6380(90)90139-Q},
	abstract = {In a study of oils and source rocks from the Kimmeridge Clay (United Kingdom)\_and the Hanifa (Qatar) Formations several biomarker maturity parameters with working ranges up to VR/E (vitrinite reflectanceequivalent) = 1.0\% (oil/condensate threshold) have been identified and calibrated. This represents a significant improvement compared to commonly used biomarker maturity tools (sterane and hopane isomerisation) with their maturity maximum of approximately VR/E = 0.7\% (early part of oil window). These new parameters are: (1) the absolute concentrations of steranes and hopanes, decreasing gradually with increasing maturity; (2) the ratio of tricyclic terpanes/(tricyclic terpanes + hopanes) increasing with maturity; (3) the ratio of diasteranes/14β(H), 17β(H)-steranes depending both on maturity and on source rock lithology, and (4) the ratio of Ts/Tm (22, 29, 30-trisnorneohopane/22, 29, 30-trisnorhopane) increasing rapidly at very high maturities. During artificial maturation experiments the biomarker maturities described in the natural samples were also known to be time/temperature-dependent up to rather severe laboratory heating conditions. This corresponds with the working range up to high maturity levels as observed in the natural samples.},
